import zipfile
import os
import glob

# Path to the uploaded zip file
zip_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/archive.zip"

# Folder where you want to extract the dataset
extract_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/lfw_dataset"

# Create the folder if it doesn't exist
os.makedirs(extract_path, exist_ok=True)

# Extract the zip file
with zipfile.ZipFile(zip_path, 'r') as zip_ref:
    zip_ref.extractall(extract_path)

print("Extraction complete!")
print("Dataset is available at:", extract_path)

import glob
import cv2
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

# Path to your extracted dataset
extract_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/lfw_dataset"

# Find all jpg images recursively
image_paths = glob.glob(os.path.join(extract_path, "**/*.jpg"), recursive=True)
print(f"Total images found: {len(image_paths)}")

# Show first 10 images
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
for i, img_path in enumerate(image_paths[:10]):
    img = cv2.imread(img_path)           # Read image
    img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)  # Convert BGR to RGB for matplotlib
    plt.subplot(2, 5, i+1)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.title(os.path.basename(os.path.dirname(img_path)))  # Show folder/person name
    plt.axis('off')

plt.show()

Total images found: 13233

In[8]:
from collections import Counter

# Count images per person
counts = Counter(labels)

# Keep only people with 2 or more images
valid_paths = [p for p in image_paths if counts[os.path.basename(os.path.dirname(p))] > 1]
valid_labels = [os.path.basename(os.path.dirname(p)) for p in valid_paths]

print(f"Total images after filtering: {len(valid_paths)}")
print(f"Total people: {len(set(valid_labels))}")

# Split dataset
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
train_paths, test_paths, train_labels, test_labels = train_test_split(
    valid_paths, valid_labels, test_size=0.2, stratify=valid_labels, random_state=42
)

Total images after filtering: 9164
Total people: 1680
In[9]:
from facenet_pytorch import InceptionResnetV1
from PIL import Image
import torch
from torchvision import transforms  # Use torchvision transforms

# Initialize model
model = InceptionResnetV1(pretrained='vggface2').eval()

# Transform PIL image to tensor
preprocess = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((160, 160)),  # FaceNet expects 160x160 images
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize([0.5, 0.5, 0.5], [0.5, 0.5, 0.5])  # normalize to [-1,1]
])

def get_embedding(image_path):
    img = Image.open(image_path).convert('RGB')
    img_tensor = preprocess(img).unsqueeze(0)  # add batch dim
    with torch.no_grad():  # no gradient needed
        embedding = model(img_tensor)
    return embedding.numpy()[0]  # 512-d vector

# Example usage
train_embeddings = [get_embedding(p) for p in train_paths[:10]]  # first 10 images
test_embeddings  = [get_embedding(p) for p in test_paths[:10]]
In[10]:
# ------------------------------
# 7 Generate embeddings
# ------------------------------
print("Generating train embeddings...")
train_embeddings = [get_embedding(p) for p in train_paths]

print("Generating test embeddings...")
test_embeddings = [get_embedding(p) for p in test_paths]

# ------------------------------
# 0 Required imports for similarity
# ------------------------------
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
import numpy as np

# ------------------------------
# 8 Predict using nearest neighbor
# ------------------------------
def predict(test_emb, train_embs, train_lbls):
    sims = cosine_similarity([test_emb], train_embs)[0]
    best_idx = np.argmax(sims)
    return train_lbls[best_idx]

print("Predicting test set...")
predicted_labels = [predict(te, train_embeddings, train_labels) for te in test_embeddings]

# ------------------------------
# 9 Calculate accuracy
# ------------------------------
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
accuracy = accuracy_score(test_labels, predicted_labels)
print(f"Face recognition accuracy: {accuracy*100:.2f}%")

Generating train embeddings...
Generating test embeddings...
Predicting test set...
Face recognition accuracy: 91.33%
In[11]:
import pickle

model_data = {
    "train_embeddings": train_embeddings,
    "train_labels": train_labels,
    "test_embeddings": test_embeddings,
    "test_labels": test_labels,
    "accuracy": accuracy,
    "facenet_model_state": model.state_dict()   # Save model weights
}

with open("attendance_model.pkl", "wb") as f:
    pickle.dump(model_data, f)

print("Model and embeddings saved successfully as attendance_model.pkl")

Model and embeddings saved successfully as attendance_model.pkl

In[12]:
# 1. Train classifier and save embeddings + model + label encoder + scaler
# Paste and run after you've produced `train_embeddings`, `train_labels`, `test_embeddings`, `test_labels`, and `accuracy`
# from the FaceNet pipeline you already ran.

import os
import pickle
import numpy as np
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

# Paths - change if you want to save to Drive
OUTPUT_PKL = "/content/drive/MyDrive/attendance_model.pkl"

# Convert lists to numpy arrays (if not already)
X_train = np.array(train_embeddings)   # shape (N_train, D)
y_train = np.array(train_labels)

X_test = np.array(test_embeddings)     # optional to keep
y_test = np.array(test_labels)

# 1) Label encode names
le = LabelEncoder()
y_train_enc = le.fit_transform(y_train)
y_test_enc = le.transform(y_test)  # will work because same labels

# 2) Optional: scale embeddings (helps some classifiers)
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled  = scaler.transform(X_test)

# 3) Train classifier - KNN is simple, fast, and works well on embeddings
clf = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3, metric='cosine', n_jobs=-1)
clf.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train_enc)

# 4) Evaluate (optional)
train_acc = clf.score(X_train_scaled, y_train_enc)
test_acc  = clf.score(X_test_scaled, y_test_enc)
print(f"Train acc: {train_acc*100:.2f}%, Test acc: {test_acc*100:.2f}%")

# 5) Save everything to a single pickle
# Also include FaceNet model.state_dict() so you can re-load weights later if needed
model_data = {
    "train_embeddings": X_train,
    "train_labels": y_train,
    "test_embeddings": X_test,
    "test_labels": y_test,
    "le": le,
    "scaler": scaler,
    "classifier": clf,
    "train_acc": float(train_acc),
    "test_acc": float(test_acc),
    # Save facenet state; make sure `model` is the InceptionResnetV1 instance in your session
    "facenet_state_dict": model.state_dict()
}

# Ensure drive path exists
os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(OUTPUT_PKL), exist_ok=True)

with open(OUTPUT_PKL, "wb") as f:
    pickle.dump(model_data, f)

print("Saved attendance model and data to:", OUTPUT_PKL)

Train acc: 92.17%, Test acc: 85.92%
Saved attendance model and data to: /content/drive/MyDrive/attendance_model.pkl
In[13]:
import pickle
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
import numpy as np
import os

# Convert to arrays
X_train = np.array(train_embeddings)
X_test  = np.array(test_embeddings)
y_train = np.array(train_labels)
y_test  = np.array(test_labels)

# Label-encode the names
le = LabelEncoder()
y_train_enc = le.fit_transform(y_train)
y_test_enc  = le.transform(y_test)

# Normalize the embeddings
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled  = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Train a small classifier on top of FaceNet embeddings
clf = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3, metric='cosine')
clf.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train_enc)

print("Train acc:", clf.score(X_train_scaled, y_train_enc))
print("Test acc :", clf.score(X_test_scaled, y_test_enc))

# Save everything in one .pkl
to_save = {
    "facenet_state_dict": model.state_dict(),
    "scaler": scaler,
    "label_encoder": le,
    "classifier": clf,
    "train_acc": clf.score(X_train_scaled, y_train_enc),
    "test_acc": clf.score(X_test_scaled, y_test_enc)
}

out_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/attendance_model.pkl"
os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(out_path), exist_ok=True)
with open(out_path, "wb") as f:
    pickle.dump(to_save, f)

print(" Saved model and all components to:", out_path)

In[15]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# pick top 20 most frequent persons
top_classes = pd.Series(y_true_names).value_counts().index[:20]

mask = [x in top_classes for x in y_true_names]
y_true_top = [t for t,m in zip(y_true_names, mask) if m]
y_pred_top = [p for p,m in zip(y_pred_names, mask) if m]

cm = confusion_matrix(y_true_top, y_pred_top, labels=top_classes)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap='Greens',
            xticklabels=top_classes,
            yticklabels=top_classes)
plt.title("Confusion Matrix - Top 20 people")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.ylabel("True")
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Calculate
train_acc = clf.score(X_train_scaled, y_train_enc)
test_acc  = clf.score(X_test_scaled, y_test_enc)

# X axis labels
x = ["Train", "Test"]

# Y values
y = [train_acc, test_acc]

plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
plt.plot(x, y, marker='o', linewidth=2)   # line with dots
plt.ylim(0,1)     # accuracy range
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.title("Train vs Test Accuracy (Line Plot)")
plt.grid(True)

# Show values on graph
for i,val in enumerate(y):
    plt.text(i, val + 0.02, f"{val*100:.2f}%")

plt.show()

import numpy as np
from collections import Counter

errors = [(true,pred) for true,pred in zip(y_true_names, y_pred_names) if true!=pred]
counter = Counter(errors)

print("Most confused persons:")
for pair,count in counter.most_common(5):
    print(pair, ":", count)

In[21]:
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity

# Use a smaller subset (otherwise it becomes huge)
subset = 50   # you can change this
X_sample = X_test_scaled[:subset]

# compute similarity matrix
sim_matrix = cosine_similarity(X_sample)

# plot heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
sns.heatmap(sim_matrix, cmap='viridis')
plt.title("Cosine Similarity Heatmap (Embeddings)")
plt.xlabel("Image Index")
plt.ylabel("Image Index")
plt.show()
